  <h2><i class="fa fa-smile-o"></i> About us</h2>

  <h3>James Vodanovich — System architect, co-founder</h3>
  <p>James believes that more organisations and individuals can successfully self-host if they are given better tools.</p>
  <p>James has designed the Engines system architecture and is writing the core system software, application builder and system services.</p>
  <p>Previous jobs include CTO of an ISP, sysadmin for a major logistics messaging network and programmer of operating software for optical multiplexers. James studied physics and started his career in research where he built data capture systems for transmission spectrometers.</p>
  <p>James loves BSD a bit too much. His favourite self-hosted application is Sonic. He was born in New Zealand and thinks that Mahara is choice.</p>
  <p>James can be found at Sydney Docker meetups and most mornings swimming at Coogee.</p>

  <h3>Lachlan Douglas — CEO, co-founder</h3>
  <p>If you get him started, Lachlan will bore you to death talking about evil Internet companies and how personal servers will become ubiquitous consumer devices. He'll then say something incomprehensible about approaching peak SAAS and web 3.0 the self-hosted web, blah, blah, blah.</p>
  <p>There's not much to do as the CEO of a two-person outfit, so Lachlan has kept busy writing the Engines management application, software library and blueprint design studio.</p>
  <p>Lachlan used to have a proper job. He was a director of an infrastructure investment firm and before that raised capital for private equity and VC funds. Lachlan has invested in startups and done other stuff that you probably don't really care about. Early on, before moving to the dark side, Lachlan designed and programmed robotic machine tools and worked in the auto industry. Lachlan studied engineering and finance.</p>
  <p>His favourite self-hosted application is ownCloud. His most used application is Redmine because that's where James logs UI bugs.</p>
  <p>Find Lachlan at Sydney Ruby/Roro meetups, although he usually leaves when the free beer runs out (thank you kind sponsors!).</p>
