  <div class="well" style="font-family:monospace;">
    <p>Dear comrades <span class='pull-right'>13 October 2015</span></p>
    <p>James and I met as students in the 90s and we've kept in touch over the years. In 2013 I'd started programming again as a hobby, tinkering with some DIY projects for private use. I needed help to deploy my personal applications on a personal server. James has been self-hosting since who knows when, so I gave him a call.</p>
    <p>After speaking about my problems we reflected on the bigger picture and how today's Internet sucks. Okay, so it doesn't all suck, but the servers that lots of people use are run by companies that suck. Duplicitous business models. Backdoors for those that would call themselves our leaders.</p>
    <p>Privacy advocates are right: the Internet has become too centralized.</p>
    <p>Talented independent developers are writing all sorts of cool server applications because they know that self-hosted and federated systems give users a better deal. But many great products go under-utilised because it's too difficult for most users to run their own server.</p>
    <p>So how can regular users easily self-host so that developers can get their software to more people? Starting in early 2014 James wrote some Bash scripts, which morphed into some Ruby classes. We tested GUI concepts, made an alpha, and have been building-out since. James has worked very hard. There are a few rough edges*, and more features to add, yet Engines is becoming a piece of work that we are proud of. We hope that you like it too.</p>
    <p>If you have a spare machine or empty VM, install the Engines beta, then install some apps and have a play. We're keen to know how you go.</p>
    <p>Lachlan<br>lachlan@engines.onl</p>
    <p><small>* bugs and crap programming to be found in my code alone. James' code is perfect. ahem.</small></p>
  </div>

